# Known bare `db.select()` joins that exceed D1's 100-column result-row cap.
# Each entry is `repo-relative/path.ts:<line>` and suppresses the ERROR exit
# code from scripts/check-d1-100col-joins.ts for that specific call site.
#
# These are real bugs (D1 silently returns zero rows when triggered) but
# they're hidden today because the queries' WHERE clauses or data state
# don't currently trigger result-rows that would exceed the cap. Each
# needs a follow-up PR that narrows the projection.
#
# Add NEW entries here only with a tracking-issue link and explicit reason.
# The CI script keeps these visible in every run so the queue stays in
# front of the team.

# ── FALSE POSITIVE — script limitation, not a real bug ────────────────────
#
# At src/lib/duplicates/merge-operations.ts:957 the audit script reports
# `events + venues + promoters + eventVendors = 116 cols`. The actual code
# is a `db.batch([...])` array containing FOUR independent `db.select()`
# calls — three of which are narrow projections like
#   `db.select({ name: venues.name }).from(venues)`
#
# Only the first is a bare `db.select().from(events)`, which is a single-
# table 62-col select (safe). The audit script's chain-detection treats
# the whole `db.batch([...])` array as one statement and sums tables from
# all contained selects, missing the per-select narrowing.
#
# Allowlisting until the script learns about `db.batch([...])` arrays.
# Tracking improvement: improve the audit script to recognize that
# `db.select(...)` calls inside `db.batch([...])` arrays are independent
# statements with their own projection arguments.
src/lib/duplicates/merge-operations.ts:957
